{{DEFAULTSORT:Abukumado}} [[Category:Background asteroids|023587]] [[Category:Discoveries by Tsutomu Seki]] [[Category:Minor planets named for places]] [[Category:Named minor planets]] [[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1995|19951002]]

'''Amardus''' or '''Mardus''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀμάρδος, Μάρδος|Amárdos,  Márdos}})<ref>[[Dionysius Periegetes|Dionys. Perieg.]], 5.734</ref> was a river of [[Media (region)|Media]], mentioned by [[Ammianus Marcellinus]] in his confused description of the Persian provinces and <ref>{{Cite Ammianus|xxiii.6}}</ref> by [[Ptolemy]] places it in Media, and if we take his numbers as correct, its source is in the [[Zagros Mountains|Zagrus]].<ref>{{Cite Ptolemy|6.2.2}}</ref> The river flows north, and enters the southern coast of the [[Caspian Sea|Caspian]]. [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]] equates the river to the modern [[Sefīd-Rūd]] river.<ref name=DGRG>{{Cite DGRG|title=Amardus}}</ref> As Ptolemy places the [[Amardi]] round the south coast of the Caspian and extending into the interior, we may suppose that they were once at least situated on and about this river.<ref name=DGRG/>

