{{Infobox protected area | name = 오대산국립공원, 五臺山國立公園 | alt_name = Odaesan National Park | iucn_category = II | photo = Korea-Gangwondo-Odaesan National Park 1663-07.JPG | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | photo_width = | map = | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_width = | location = | nearest_city = | coords = {{coord|37|47|43|N|128|32|35|E}} | coords_ref = | area = {{convert|303.93|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref name="knps.or.kr">{{cite web |url=http://english.knps.or.kr/Knp/Odaesan/Intro/Introduction.aspx?MenuNum=1&Submenu=Npp |title=Odaesan: Intro |author= |date= |website= |publisher=Korea National Park Service |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> | established = 1 February 1975 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = Korea National Park Service | world_heritage_site = | url = }}
{{see also|Odaesan}} '''Odaesan National Park''' ({{lang-ko|'''오대산국립공원''', '''五臺山國立公園'''}}) is located in the province of [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon-do]], [[South Korea]]. It was first designated as the 11th national park in 1975.<ref name="knps.or.kr" /> The park is named after the {{convert|1563|m|ft|adj=on}} mountain [[Odaesan]], which means "Five Plains Mountain", named after the five plains between the area's five major peaks.<ref name="Hae-Jin Lee366">{{cite book |title=Frommer's South Korea |last=Hae-Jin Lee |first=Cecilia |year=2010 |publisher=[[Frommer's]] |isbn=978-0-470-59154-3 |page=366 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95HEb92jABoC&pg=PA366 }}</ref> The park is home to a total of 3,788 species: 1,040 plant species, 28 mammal species, 103 bird species, 13 amphibian species, 12 reptile species, 35 fish species, 1,976 insect species and 157 spider species.<ref name="knps.or.kr" /> {{stack|[[File:Odesan Park in Autumn, Korea.jpg|thumb|260px|Odesan Park in Autumn]]}} {{South Korea national parks}} The park has some tourist amenities such as campgrounds, walking paths, and pension-style accommodations.
